    > >
    > > ## 5. Behavioral Skills (Karpathy-Inspired)
    > >
    > > These apply across specification and implementation. They are concrete, enforceable rules.
    > >
    > > ## 5.1 Think Before Coding
    > >
    > > For every `/kiro:spec-design`, `/kiro:spec-tasks`, and `/kiro:spec-impl`:
    > >
    > > - Explicitly state key assumptions (1–3 items) about:
    > >   - Requirements,
    > >   - Domain behavior,
    > >   - Constraints from docs/skills.
    > > - If multiple interpretations or implementation paths exist:
    > >   - List at least 2 options briefly.
    > >   - Explain why one is chosen for now.
    > > - If something in `docs/` or specs is unclear:
    > >   - Stop, name what is confusing.
    > >   - Ask for clarification instead of guessing silently.
    > >
    > > These assumptions should appear in either the spec design, tasks, or the Pre-Coding Dry Run section.
    > >
    > > ## 5.2 Simplicity First
    > >
    > > Within the boundaries of authority docs:
    > >
    > > - Implement the minimum code that solves the current spec and tasks.
    > > - No speculative features, configurations, or flexibility that are not requested.
    > > - No abstractions for single-use code (e.g. generic factories for one caller).
    > > - Do not add error handling for scenarios declared impossible in docs.
    > > - If you notice that a solution could be much shorter (e.g. 200 lines → 50 lines):
    > >   - Prefer the simpler solution.
    > >   - For non-trivial simplifications, briefly note the reasoning in the design or Dry Run.
    > >
    > > When docs already prescribe a complex structure, do not “simplify away” the required structure. Simplicity applies to decisions that are left open by design.
    > >
    > > ## 5.3 Surgical Changes
    > >
    > > When editing existing code in `/kiro:spec-impl`:
    > >
    > > - Touch only what is required by:
    > >   - The current spec tasks, and
    > >   - The Impact Surface defined in the Dry Run.
    > > - Do NOT:
    > >   - “Improve” adjacent code, comments, or formatting unrelated to this spec.
    > >   - Refactor unrelated modules or flows unless explicitly requested.
    > > - Match existing style, even if you personally would do it differently.
    > > - If your changes create orphans (unused imports, variables, functions):
    > >   - Remove only the orphans that your changes created.
    > >   - Do not remove pre-existing dead code unless explicitly requested.
    > > - All changed lines MUST be traceable to:
    > >   - An item in the spec tasks, or
    > >   - A clearly recorded deviation in the Deviation Report.
    > >
    > > If you must modify files outside the initial Impact Surface, you MUST update Impact Surface and record it in the Deviation Report.
    > >
    > > ## 5.4 Goal-Driven Execution
    > >
    > > For multi-step work:
    > >
    > > - Transform vague tasks into verifiable goals.
    > >
    > >   - “Add validation” → “Write tests for invalid inputs, then make them pass.”
    > >   - “Fix the bug” → “Write a test that reproduces it, then make it pass.”
    > >
    > > - Before implementing, write a short plan:
    > >
    > >   ```
    > >   text
    > >   1) Step [X] → verify: [check or test]
    > >   2) Step [Y] → verify: [check or test]
    > >   3) Step [Z] → verify: [check or test]
    > >   ```
    > >
    > > - Define 2–5 success criteria per spec-impl run and, during `/kiro:validate-impl`, explicitly confirm:
    > >
    > >   - Which criteria are met,
    > >   - Which are pending or failed (and why).
    > >
    > > ------
    > >
    > > ## 6. Development SOP (Documentation‑First, Mandatory)
    > >
    > > This SOP is a **hard constraint**. Non-compliant runs are considered invalid and must be discarded or re-run.
    > >
    > > ## 6.1 Authority & Traceability
    > >
    > > - Treat `docs/*.md` and `docs/skills/*.md` as authority sources for:
    > >
    > >   - Domain behavior,
    > >   - Flows,
    > >   - Public contracts,
    > >   - Project structure.
    > >
    > > - Steering is a concise summary layer and index; it MUST point to authority docs via Authority Anchors.
    > >
    > > - Conflict resolution priority:
    > >
    > >   ```
    > >   text
    > >   docs/ & docs/skills/ (authority)
    > >     > active spec documents
    > >     > steering summary
    > >     > existing code shape
    > >   ```
    > >
    > > ## 6.2 Project Structure Contract
    > >
    > > Define and obey a project structure contract (documented in `structure.md` and/or dedicated doc):
    > >
    > > - Allowed top-level directories and responsibilities (e.g. `src/`, `tests/`, `docs/`, `internal/`).
    > > - Layering and location rules:
    > >   - HTTP handlers, use-cases, repositories, domain models, etc.
    > > - Naming conventions:
    > >   - Service interfaces, implementations, DTOs, test files, etc.
    > >
    > > Rules:
    > >
    > > - Before creating any new file or directory:
    > >   - Check it against the Project Structure Contract.
    > > - Creating a file or directory that violates the contract is a deviation:
    > >   - Classify as minor or major in the Deviation Report.
    > >   - Do not hide structural deviations.
    > >
    > > ## 6.3 Mandatory Output Sections for `/kiro:spec-impl`
    > >
    > > Every implementation run MUST output the following sections in order:
    > >
    > > 1. **Authority Anchors**
    > >
    > >    - `Docs Sources:` (list of docs/ and/or skills used)
    > >      - `docs/auth/login.md#http-api`
    > >      - `docs/structure/services.md#auth-service`
    > >      - `docs/skills/auth/login-flow.md`
    > >
    > > 2. **Pre-Coding Dry Run**
    > >
    > >    - `Assumptions:`
    > >      Key assumptions about requirements / domain / constraints.
    > >    - `Impact Surface:`
    > >      Files/modules/tests to be created or modified.
    > >    - `Design Delta:`
    > >      Whether and where implementation will differ from authority design.
    > >    - `Execution Decision:`
    > >      Follow design exactly vs. request deviation handling.
    > >
    > >    If this Dry Run section is missing or incomplete, do NOT start coding.
    > >
    > > 3. **Implementation Plan (Bound to Docs)**
    > >
    > >    - A short ordered list of steps that explicitly reference authority docs/skills.
    > >
    > >    - Example:
    > >
    > >      ```
    > >      text
    > >      1) Implement HTTP handler in src/http/auth/login_handler.ts
    > >         based on docs/auth/login.md#http-api.
    > >      2) Implement use-case in src/app/auth/login_usecase.ts
    > >         based on docs/skills/auth/login-flow.md.
    > >      3) Add tests according to docs/auth/login.md#test-cases.
    > >      ```
    > >
    > > 4. **Deviation Report**
    > >
    > >    - `Deviation Type:` `major | minor | none`
    > >    - `Description:` what differs from docs/spec/structure.
    > >    - `Reason:` why deviation is necessary.
    > >    - `Impact Surface Changes:` any files touched beyond the original Impact Surface.
    > >    - `Approval Status:` `pending | approved | rejected` (for human reviewers).
    > >
    > >    Any implementation without an explicit Deviation Report (even if `none`) is invalid.
    > >
    > > 5. **Post-Implementation Conformance Check**
    > >
    > >    - Provide a short checklist comparing final code against:
    > >      - Project Structure Contract.
    > >      - Authority docs (flows, contracts).
    > >      - Defined success criteria.
    > >    - For each item, mark `pass` / `fail` and explain failures briefly.
    > >    - Any failed item MUST be reflected in the Deviation Report or TODOs.
    > >
    > > ## 6.4 Task Granularity Constraints
    > >
    > > - A single `/kiro:spec-impl` run MUST NOT:
    > >   - Introduce or modify more than a configured number of files, or
    > >   - Change more than a configured number of public endpoints/classes.
    > > - If the planned Impact Surface is too large:
    > >   - Split into multiple spec tasks and smaller implementation runs.
    > > - This limits long-running, drifting implementations and keeps deviations observable.
    > >
    > > ## 6.5 Non-Compliance Is an Error
    > >
    > > Any implementation run that does not:
    > >
    > > - Reference relevant authority docs/skills in **Authority Anchors**,
    > > - Provide a complete **Pre-Coding Dry Run**,
    > > - Produce a **Deviation Report** (with `none` if truly no deviation),
    > > - Run a **Post-Implementation Conformance Check**,
    > >
    > > MUST be considered invalid. The correct response is to:
    > >
    > > - Discard the result (do not merge),
    > > - Or re-run the implementation with full SOP compliance.
    > >
    > > ------
    > >
    > > ## 7. Example: Spec-Impl Output Skeleton
    > >
    > > For a feature like `user-auth/login`, a compliant `/kiro:spec-impl` output skeleton:
    > >
    > > ```
    > > text
    > > Authority Anchors
    > > - docs/auth/login.md#http-api
    > > - docs/structure/services.md#auth-service
    > > - docs/skills/auth/login-flow.md
    > > 
    > > Pre-Coding Dry Run
    > > - Assumptions:
    > >   - Login uses email + password only.
    > >   - No MFA in this iteration.
    > > - Impact Surface:
    > >   - src/http/auth/login_handler.ts
    > >   - src/app/auth/login_usecase.ts
    > >   - tests/http/auth/login_handler.spec.ts
    > > - Design Delta:
    > >   - None, follow docs exactly.
    > > - Execution Decision:
    > >   - Proceed with authority design; no deviations planned.
    > > 
    > > Implementation Plan (Bound to Docs)
    > > 1) Implement HTTP handler per docs/auth/login.md#http-api.
    > > 2) Implement use-case per docs/skills/auth/login-flow.md.
    > > 3) Add tests per docs/auth/login.md#test-cases.
    > > 
    > > Deviation Report
    > > - Deviation Type: none
    > > - Description: N/A
    > > - Reason: N/A
    > > - Impact Surface Changes: none
    > > - Approval Status: pending (for human review)
    > > 
    > > Post-Implementation Conformance Check
    > > - Project Structure Contract: pass
    > > - HTTP contracts vs docs/auth/login.md#http-api: pass
    > > - Flow vs docs/skills/auth/login-flow.md: pass
    > > - Success Criteria:
    > >   - Invalid credential tests: pass
    > >   - Locked account tests: pass
    > >   - Logging requirements: pass
    > > ```
    > >
